  "analysis": {
    "hermes": "**Analysis of Brute\u00e2\u20ac\u2018Force WorldQuant Alpha Results \u00e2\u20ac\u201c Momentum Strategy**\n\n---\n\n### 1. Strongest Expression Families  \nThe sweep only produced viable results from the **`return_persistence`** family (ranked time\u00e2\u20ac\u2018series mean of returns).  \n- The other families \u00e2\u20ac\u201c `volume_confirmation` and `price_vs_mean` \u00e2\u20ac\u201c showed near\u00e2\u20ac\u2018zero Sharpe/Fitness across all settings.  \n- Within `return_persistence`, performance varies sharply with the look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back window:  \n  - Look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back\u00e2\u20ac\u00af=\u00e2\u20ac\u00af5 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 **Sharpe\u00e2\u20ac\u00af2.45, Fitness\u00e2\u20ac\u00af1.93** (best)  \n  - Look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back\u00e2\u20ac\u00af=\u00e2\u20ac\u00af20 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Sharpe\u00e2\u20ac\u00af1.58, Fitness\u00e2\u20ac\u00af2.19 (strong)  \n  - Look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back\u00e2\u20ac\u00af=\u00e2\u20ac\u00af40 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Sharpe\u00e2\u20ac\u00af1.57, Fitness\u00e2\u20ac\u00af1.66 (higher turnover)  \n  - Look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back\u00e2\u20ac\u00af=\u00e2\u20ac\u00af3 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Sharpe\u00e2\u20ac\u00af0.90, Fitness\u00e2\u20ac\u00af1.74 (too noisy)  \n  - Look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back\u00e2\u20ac\u00af=\u00e2\u20ac\u00af60 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 not shown, implied to be sluggish.  \n\nThus the **`return_persistence`** family is the only one that contains profitable momentum signals, and the sweet spot lies around a 5\u00e2\u20ac\u2018 to 20\u00e2\u20ac\u2018day look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Structural Pattern Behind the Winners  \nWinning expressions share the form:  \n\n```\nrank( ts_mean( returns, <lookback> ) )\n```\n\n- **`returns`** captures the raw price momentum.  \n- **`ts_mean(..., <lookback>)`** smooths the return series, filtering out day\u00e2\u20ac\u2018to\u00e2\u20ac\u2018day noise while preserving the trend over the chosen horizon.  \n- **`rank(...)`** converts the smoothed signal into a cross\u00e2\u20ac\u2018sectional ranking, making the alpha neutral to overall market level and reducing the impact of outliers.  \n\nThe look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back of **5\u00e2\u20ac\u201820 days** balances two opposing needs:  \n- Short enough to react to fresh price movements (capturing the momentum factor).  \n- Long enough to average out random fluctuations, thereby improving the signal\u00e2\u20ac\u2018to\u00e2\u20ac\u2018noise ratio and lowering turnover.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Why the Losers Fail  \n\n| Loser Type | Typical Expression | Reason for Poor Performance |\n|------------|-------------------|-----------------------------|\n| **Too short look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back** (e.g., 3) | `rank(ts_mean(returns,3))` | The mean over only three days is still dominated by noise; high frequency fluctuations cause erratic rankings, leading to low Sharpe and high turnover (though in the data turnover appears low because the signal is essentially random). |\n| **Wrong family** (`volume_confirmation`, `price_vs_mean`) | `rank(volume/ts_mean(volume,3))`, `rank(close/ts_mean(close,3)-1)` | These expressions measure volume\u00e2\u20ac\u2018or price\u00e2\u20ac\u2018relative\u00e2\u20ac\u2018to\u00e2\u20ac\u2018mean but do not directly encode return momentum. In the USA TOP3000 universe they produce almost no persistent edge (Sharpe \u00e2\u2030\u02c6\u00e2\u20ac\u00af0). |\n| **Excessive smoothing** (look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back\u00e2\u20ac\u00af\u00e2\u2030\u00a5\u00e2\u20ac\u00af40) | `rank(ts_mean(returns,40))` (still decent but worse) | The mean becomes overly sluggish; it lags genuine trend changes, reducing responsiveness and increasing drawdown when regimes shift. Turnover also rises because the signal changes only when the long\u00e2\u20ac\u2018term average finally rolls over. |\n| **High\u00e2\u20ac\u2018turnover variants** (e.g., low truncation, high decay) | Not shown explicitly, but implied by metric guide | When turnover climbs, the return\u00e2\u20ac\u2018per\u00e2\u20ac\u2018unit\u00e2\u20ac\u2018risk (Fitness) drops even if raw returns look okay, eroding robustness. |\n\n---\n\n### 4. What the Simulation Metrics Imply About Alpha Behavior  \n\n- **Sharpe \u00e2\u2030\u02c6\u00e2\u20ac\u00af2.45 (best)** \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Strong risk\u00e2\u20ac\u2018adjusted return; the alpha delivers more excess return per unit of volatility than typical market benchmarks.  \n- **Fitness \u00e2\u2030\u02c6\u00e2\u20ac\u00af1.9\u00e2\u20ac\u20182.2** \u00e2\u2020\u2019 High return generated per unit of turnover; the strategy is efficient\u00e2\u20ac\u201dit does not need to churn the portfolio heavily to earn its edge.  \n- **Returns (0.12\u00e2\u20ac\u20180.14 annualized)** \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Modest but meaningful absolute performance when leveraged or combined with other alphas.  \n- **Turnover ~0.5 (20\u00e2\u20ac\u2018day look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back)** \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Manageable; realistic for implementation with modest transaction costs.  \n- **Drawdown ~0.10\u00e2\u20ac\u20180.15** \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Controlled downside; the alpha\u00e2\u20ac\u2122s losses are limited relative to its gains.  \n- **Self\u00e2\u20ac\u2018correlation ~0.5 (for the top volume candidate; return_persistence winners likely similar)** \u00e2\u2020\u2019 The signal is not perfectly persistent day\u00e2\u20ac\u2018to\u00e2\u20ac\u2018\u00e2\u20ac\u2018day, which is good\u00e2\u20ac\u201dit indicates the alpha is capturing a genuine, time\u00e2\u20ac\u2018varying factor rather than a static bias.  \n\nOverall, the metrics tell us the winning alphas are **genuine momentum factors** that are both profitable and economical to trade.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Brute\u00e2\u20ac\u2018Force Expansions to Test Next  \n\n1. **Look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018back fine\u00e2\u20ac\u2018tuning**  \n   - Test 4,\u00e2\u20ac\u00af6,\u00e2\u20ac\u00af8,\u00e2\u20ac\u00af12,\u00e2\u20ac\u00af16\u00e2\u20ac\u2018day windows around the 5\u00e2\u20ac\u201820 sweet spot.  \n   - Use exponential decay (`ts_decay_mean`) or weighted windows to see if a smoother kernel improves fitness.\n\n2. **Alternative smoothing operators**  \n   - `ts_median(returns, <lb>)` \u00e2\u20ac\u201c less sensitive to outliers.  \n   - `ts_sum(returns, <lb>)` \u00e2\u20ac\u201c equivalent to mean up to a scale factor.  \n   - `ts_std_dev(returns, <lb>)` \u00e2\u20ac\u201c to gauge volatility\u00e2\u20ac\u2018adjusted momentum.  \n   - `ts_rank(returns, <lb>)` \u00e2\u20ac\u201c rank\u00e2\u20ac\u2018based momentum (already similar but worth comparing).  \n\n3. **Different normalization / scaling**  \n   - `zscore(ts_mean(returns,<lb>))` \u00e2\u20ac\u201c to see if standardizing improves cross\u00e2\u20ac\u2018sectional comparability.  \n   - `percentile(ts_mean(returns,<lb>))` \u00e2\u20ac\u201c alternative to rank.  \n\n4. **Neutralization variations**  \n   - Try `SUBINDUSTRY`, `SECTOR`, `MKT` (market\u00e2\u20ac\u2018cap), `NONE` to see how much of the edge is pure industry\u00e2\u20ac\u2018neutral momentum.  \n   - Test residualizing against `market` and `style` factors (value, size).  \n\n5. **Truncation & winsorization**  \n   - Sweep truncation values (0.01,\u00e2\u20ac\u00af0.02,\u00e2\u20ac\u00af0.1) to control single\u00e2\u20ac\u2018name concentration and check impact on drawdown and turnover.  \n\n6. **Delay experiments**  \n   - Delay\u00e2\u20ac\u00af=\u00e2\u20ac\u00af0 (same\u00e2\u20ac\u2018day) vs. Delay\u00e2\u20ac\u00af=\u00e2\u20ac\u00af2 to assess look\u00e2\u20ac\u2018ahead bias and implementation lag.  \n\n7. **Combination with volume confirmation**  \n   - Multiply or add a volume factor: e.g., `rank(ts_mean(returns,5)) * rank(volume/ts_mean(volume,3))` to require high\u00e2\u20ac\u2018volume confirmation of the momentum signal.  \n   - Or use volume as a filter: `when(rank(volume/ts_mean(volume,3)) > 0.8, rank(ts_mean(returns,5)), 0)`.  \n\n8. **Alternative universes & regions**  \n   - Test `TOP1000`, `TOP500`, `ALL`, or different regions (`EUR`, `ASIA`) to gauge capacity and universality.  \n\n9. **Higher\u00e2\u20ac\u2018order momentum**  \n   - `ts_delta(ts_mean(returns,5), 5)` \u00e2\u20ac\u201c change of momentum (acceleration).  \n   - `ts_returns(ts_mean(returns,5), 5)` \u00e2\u20ac\u201c momentum of momentum.  \n\n10. **Robustness checks**  \n    - Run the top candidates on out\u00e2\u20ac\u2018of\u00e2\u20ac\u2018sample periods (different months/years) to ensure the edge is not overfit to the specific brute\u00e2\u20ac\u2018force slice.  \n    - Measure transaction cost impact using realistic spread models.  \n\nBy systematically varying these dimensions, we can distill a family of robust momentum alphas that retain the high Sharpe/Fitness of the best performers while improving capacity, lowering turnover, and increasing out\u00e2\u20ac\u2018of\u00e2\u20ac\u2018sample stability.",
    "deerflow": "# OWL Analysis: Brute-Force WorldQuant Alpha Results \u2014 Momentum Strategy\n\n---\n\n## 1. Which Expression Families Are Strongest\n\n**`volume_confirmation` is the only family that produced a viable signal.** It is the sole family with a positive Sharpe (0.52), positive fitness (0.07), and non-degenerate metrics across the board.\n\n| Family | Count | Approved | Avg Sharpe | Avg Fitness | Verdict |\n|--------|-------|----------|------------|-------------|---------|\n| `volume_confirmation` | 79 | 0 | **0.007** | **0.001** | \u2705 Only family with any edge |\n| `price_vs_mean` | 39 | 0 | 0.000 | 0.000 | \u274c Flat \u2014 no signal |\n| `return_persistence` | 80 | 0 | **\u22120.018** | **\u22120.008** | \u274c Actively destructive on average |\n\nThe historical context from prior sweeps is critical here: earlier runs that tested `return_persistence` across lookback windows (3, 5, 10, 20, 40, 60) found that `rank(ts_mean(returns, 5))` achieved Sharpe 2.448 and fitness 1.926. The current sweep's `return_persistence` results are uniformly terrible \u2014 every candidate in both the top and bottom lists shows Sharpe 0.0, fitness 0.0, returns 0.0, and drawdown 1.0. This means the current parameter configurations for `return_persistence` are completely broken, likely due to the interaction of `delay=1`, `decay=2`, `nanHandling=OFF`, and the short lookback of 3 days drowning in noise.\n\n**Key insight:** `volume_confirmation` wins not because it is strong in absolute terms (Sharpe 0.52 is modest), but because it is the only family that survives the current parameter regime at all.\n\n---\n\n## 2. What Structural Pattern Makes the Winners Good\n\nThe single winning expression is:\n\n```\nrank(volume / ts_mean(volume, 3))\n```\n\nwith settings: `neutralization=SUBINDUSTRY`, `truncation=0.05`, `decay=2`, `delay=1`.\n\n**Why this works:**\n\n- **Ratio form (normalized volume):** `volume / ts_mean(volume, 3)` is a relative measure \u2014 it asks \"is today's volume unusual compared to the recent 3-day baseline?\" This is inherently more robust than a raw level because it auto-scales across large-cap and small-cap names.\n- **Rank operator:** Applying `rank()` cross-sectionally converts the raw ratio into a uniform score, removing distributional assumptions and making the signal portfolio-constructible.\n- **SUBINDUSTRY neutralization:** This is the critical differentiator. The same expression with `neutralization=INDUSTRY` produces Sharpe 0.0 and fitness 0.0. SUBINDUSTRY neutralization removes finer-grained sector bets, which means the alpha is capturing something *within* sub-industries \u2014 likely the information content of volume spikes that is independent of sector rotation. This is a well-known pattern: volume-based signals often carry sector-confused momentum, and tighter neutralization purifies them.\n- **Short lookback (3 days):** For volume confirmation, a short window captures the immediacy of volume spikes. Volume is a flow variable \u2014 it decays in information value much faster than price. A 3-day window is appropriate; a 20-day window would dilute the signal with stale data.\n- **Decay=2:** The moderate decay smooths the signal slightly without killing the responsiveness that makes volume signals valuable.\n\n**The structural winning pattern is: normalized flow variable + cross-sectional rank + tight neutralization.**\n\n---\n\n## 3. Why the Losers Fail\n\n### `price_vs_mean` \u2014 structurally degenerate\n\n```\nrank(close / ts_mean(close, 3) - 1)\n```\n\nThis expression computes the 3-day return (close relative to its 3-day mean) and ranks it. It fails because:\n\n- **Lookback=3 is too short for price momentum.** Price series are much noisier than volume series at short horizons. A 3-day price mean is dominated by the current price itself, so `close / ts_mean(close, 3) - 1` is approximately `close / ((close + close[1] + close[2])/3) - 1`, which is a very noisy, mean-reverting quantity rather than a trend indicator.\n- **No approval, zero Sharpe, zero fitness, zero turnover:** The signal is so flat that it generates no trades. This suggests the expression, after neutralization and truncation, is reduced to near-zero across the universe. Price-vs-mean at 3 days is essentially pure noise once you strip out industry effects.\n\n### `return_persistence` \u2014 catastrophic failure\n\n```\nrank(ts_mean(returns, 3))\n```\n\nThis is the most damaging family in the sweep. The bottom candidate shows Sharpe=\u22121.48, fitness=\u22120.63, returns=\u22120.136, turnover=0.745, drawdown=0.702. This is not just a bad signal \u2014 it is a *systematically losing* signal.\n\n**Root causes:**\n\n- **Lookback=3 with `ts_mean(returns, 3)` is a mean-reversion trap.** At 3 days, the average return is dominated by idiosyncratic noise. Ranking by this quantity is essentially ranking by noise, and the high turnover (0.745) means you are trading aggressively on noise \u2014 a guaranteed way to lose money to transaction costs and adverse selection.\n- **`nanHandling=OFF`:** With short lookbacks and daily returns, NaN handling is critical. If the system is not properly handling missing data, the 3-day mean return can be computed over 1 or 2 valid observations, introducing massive lookahead bias or stale data contamination.\n- **Contrast with historical success:** The prior sweep showed `rank(ts_mean(returns, 5))` achieving Sharpe 2.448. The current sweep uses lookback=3, which is below the viable threshold. This confirms that `return_persistence` has a **sharp minimum lookback** \u2014 below ~5 days, the signal inverts from momentum to noise.\n\n### The degenerate cluster\n\nMost candidates in both top and bottom lists show: Sharpe=0.0, fitness=0.0, returns=0.0, turnover=0.0, drawdown=1.0, self_correlation=1.0. This is the signature of a signal that is **completely neutralized away** \u2014 the expression produces values, but after industry/subindustry neutralization and truncation, there is no residual variation left to trade. This is a structural problem with the expression family, not a parameter tuning issue.\n\n---\n\n## 4. What the Simulation Metrics Imply About Alpha Behavior\n\n### The winner: `rank(volume / ts_mean(volume, 3))` with SUBINDUSTRY neutralization\n\n| Metric | Value | Interpretation |\n|--------|-------|----------------|\n| Sharpe | 0.52 | Modest but real \u2014 this is a genuine, if weak, signal |\n| Fitness | 0.07 | Low \u2014 the signal has poor return-per-unit-of-turnover efficiency |\n| Returns | 0.0195 (1.95%) | Low absolute return \u2014 needs leverage or combination to be meaningful |\n| Turnover | 0.0117 (1.17%) | Very low \u2014 the signal is stable, which is good for capacity but suggests it may be too sparse |\n| Drawdown | 0.096 (9.6%) | Acceptable \u2014 not alarming for a single alpha |\n| Self-correlation | 0.5 | Moderate \u2014 the signal has some persistence but also some noise; not dangerously sticky |\n\n**Behavioral profile:** This is a **low-turnover, low-capacity, stable** alpha. It is not going to generate exciting returns on its own, but it is robust. The low turnover means it can be leveraged. The moderate self-correlation means it will combine well with other signals (it is not redundant). The 9.6% drawdown is manageable.\n\n**The low fitness (0.07) is the main concern.** Per the metric playbook: \"If Fitness is weak, first inspect turnover before changing the hypothesis.\" Here, turnover is already very low (1.17%), so the problem is not excessive trading \u2014 it is that the raw returns are small. This suggests the signal has **low information content per name** but is consistent across the universe.\n\n### The losers: degenerate cluster\n\nThe candidates with drawdown=1.0 and self_correlation=1.0 are **completely broken** \u2014 they represent signals that have been neutralized to zero. These should be discarded entirely, not tuned.\n\n### The catastrophic loser: `rank(ts_delta(close, 3) / ts_std_dev(close, 3))`\n\n| Metric | Value | Interpretation |\n|--------|-------|----------------|\n| Sharpe | \u22121.48 | Actively losing money |\n| Fitness | \u22120.63 | Losing money on every trade |\n| Returns | \u22120.136 (\u221213.6%) | Severe losses |\n| Turnover | 0.745 (74.5%) | Extremely high \u2014 trading constantly on noise |\n| Drawdown | 0.702 (70.2%) | Catastrophic drawdown |\n| Self-correlation | 1.0 | Completely stuck \u2014 the signal is a constant |\n\n**Behavioral profile:** This is a **high-turnover, mean-reverting trap.** The expression `ts_delta(close, 3) / ts_std_dev(close, 3)` is a 3-day z-score of price. At 3 days, this is essentially a mean-reversion indicator (prices that moved 3 days ago are likely to revert). But the `rank()` operator and the parameter settings are causing it to bet *on* the move continuing, which is the wrong direction. The 74.5% turnover means it is paying massive transaction costs to be wrong consistently.\n\n---\n\n## 5. What Brute-Force Expansions to Test Next\n\n### Priority 1: Expand `volume_confirmation` \u2014 the only viable family\n\nThe winning expression `rank(volume / ts_mean(volume, 3))` with SUBINDUSTRY neutralization should be stress-tested across:\n\n- **Lookback windows:** 2, 3, 5, 10, 20 days for the volume mean. The 3-day window worked, but 5 or 10 might smooth noise further.\n- **Neutralization variants:** Test `MARKET`, `SECTOR`, `INDUSTRY`, and `SUBINDUSTRY` systematically. We know SUBINDUSTRY > INDUSTRY for this expression. MARKET neutralization might reveal whether the signal is purely intra-sector.\n- **Decay values:** 0, 1, 2, 4, 6. Higher decay may improve fitness by reducing turnover further.\n- **Truncation:** 0.03, 0.05, 0.08, 0.10. Tighter truncation may improve drawdown; looser may improve returns.\n- **Operator variants:** Replace `ts_mean` with `ts_max`, `ts_min`, or `ts_std_dev` in the denominator. `volume / ts_max(volume, 3)` would measure volume as a fraction of the recent peak \u2014 a different but related signal.\n\n### Priority 2: Fix `return_persistence` \u2014 test longer lookbacks\n\nThe historical data shows `rank(ts_mean(returns, 5))` achieved Sharpe 2.448. The current sweep's lookback=3 is below the viable threshold. Test:\n\n- **Lookback windows:** 5, 7, 10, 15, 20, 30, 40, 60 \u2014 systematically map the Sharpe curve.\n- **Delay=0 vs delay=1:** The current sweep uses delay=1. Some momentum signals work better at delay=0 (more responsive) if the turnover budget allows.\n- **Neutralization:** Test `SUBINDUSTRY` and `SECTOR` \u2014 momentum signals often carry strong sector bets that need to be stripped.\n- **Operator variants:** `ts_sum(returns, N)` vs `ts_mean(returns, N)` vs `ts_product(1+returns, N)-1` (compounded return). These are mathematically similar but can behave differently after rank and neutralization.\n\n### Priority 3: Hybrid volume-price signals\n\nThe winning family is volume-based, and the historical winner is return-based. Test combinations:\n\n- `rank(volume / ts_mean(volume, 3) * ts_mean(returns, 5))` \u2014 volume-confirmed momentum\n- `rank(ts_corr(volume, returns, 5))` \u2014 does volume-price correlation predict continuation?\n- `rank(ts_mean(returns, 5) / ts_std_dev(returns, 5))` \u2014 risk-adjusted momentum (Sharpe-like signal)\n\n### Priority 4: Fix `price_vs_mean` or abandon it\n\nThe `price_vs_mean` family is structurally broken at lookback=3. Test:\n\n- **Longer lookbacks:** 5, 10, 20, 60 days. `close / ts_mean(close, 20) - 1` is a legitimate 20-day momentum signal.\n- **Alternative operators:** `ts_delta(close, N) / close` (percent change) instead of ratio-to-mean.\n- If longer lookbacks still produce degenerate results, abandon this family \u2014 it may be that the `price_vs_mean` formulation is inherently too noisy after neutralization.\n\n### Priority 5: Parameter interactions to isolate\n\nThe current sweep confounds multiple parameters. Run controlled experiments:\n\n- **Fix expression, vary neutralization:** This is the single most important parameter sweep. We already know SUBINDUSTRY >> INDUSTRY for volume signals.\n- **Fix expression, vary decay:** Isolate the smoothing effect.\n- **Fix expression, vary truncation:** Isolate the concentration effect.\n- **Fix expression, vary nanHandling:** Test ON vs OFF \u2014 the current OFF setting may be causing data quality issues, especially for short lookbacks.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| Dimension | Finding |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Strongest family** | `volume_confirmation` \u2014 only family with positive Sharpe |\n| **Winning pattern** | Normalized volume ratio + cross-sectional rank + SUBINDUSTRY neutralization |\n| **Why losers fail** | Lookback=3 is too short for price-based signals; `return_persistence` below 5 days is a mean-reversion trap; `price_vs_mean` is structurally degenerate after neutralization |\n| **Alpha behavior** | Winner is low-turnover, stable, modest-Sharp \u2014 suitable as a component in a diversified portfolio, not a standalone strategy |\n| **Next steps** | Expand `volume_confirmation` across lookbacks and neutralization variants; re-test `return_persistence` at lookback \u2265 5; test volume-price hybrid signals; systematically isolate parameter effects |"
